CMSC320 Final Tutorial: Worldwide CO2 Emission Suvery & Prediction¶

By: Jie Chen

Introduction¶

Global warming is one of the biggest challenges humanities are facing nowadays. According to charts comparison provided by Bloomberg at https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2015-whats-warming-the-world/. The biggest contributor to the global warming is greenhouse gases. CO2 (Carbon dioxide) is one of them. By anaylizing the worldwide historical carbon dioxide emission in recent years, it will give us a better understanding on key questions, such as who emits the most CO2, and the trends CO2 emission per person based on geographic regions.

Import Libraries¶

Before we can get started working with the tutorial, we will need to import the following necessary modules and setup some configurations. There are chances that some of the modules are not pre-installed into your local machine. Therefore, it is important to console with each module's official documentation page in regards to how to install the packages.

Data¶

The World Bank Data https://data.worldbank.org/ provides a comprehensive dataset on a variety of subjects based on countries and regions. They offer thousands of indicators ranging from economic data such as GDP, incomes, and the poverty rate; to environmental data such as numbers of endanger species, forest area, and clean water resources.

In this tutorial, we will be using two datasets from the World Bank Data. One is the global CO2 data, and another one is the population data. Both datasets were retrieved and updated from World Bank Data on December 10, 2017. It was localized on the local machine to avoid constant re-downloading the data.

To retrieve an up to date CO2 emission data in CSV format, please visit the website: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/EN.ATM.CO2E.KT, and click Download CSV link on the right hand side. Other formats such as Excel and XML are also available.

To retrieve the up to date population data, please visit: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.POP.TOTL.

In the CO2 emission data zip file, it contains three CSV files:

File Name
API_EN.ATM.CO2E.KT_DS2_en_csv_v2.csv
Metadata_Country_API_EN.ATM.CO2E.KT_DS2_en_csv_v2.csv
Metadata_Indicator_API_EN.ATM.CO2E.KT_DS2_en_csv_v2.csv

We will be using the first two CSV files in this tutorial.

There are also three CSV files in the population zip file. However, we are only going to use included API_SP.POP.TOTL_DS2_en_csv_v2.csv file.

Data Preprocessing¶

Important Note: The original CSV files contained in the zip files downloaded from the World Bank cannot be directly imported into the Python panda's DataFrame due to formatting/encoding issues. CO2 dataset and population dataset has four extra descriptive rows at the beginning of the file that does not fit into CSV column standard. Additionally, all dataframe imported from CSV files will have an unnamed column at the end with NaN values as the reason unknown. Therefore, all CSV files were opened with Microsoft's Excel and row the descriptive rows if needed. They were subsequently exported to a CSV file in latin-1 encoding.

Tidy The DataFrames¶

To optimize the CO2 dataframe for easier processing later on, we will now tiding the CO2 DF. To do so, we will need to define the observation, variable, and value of the DF. To read more information regarding tidy data, please visit: https://www.jstatsoft.org/article/view/v059i10/v59i10.pdf. In this case, the observation is the Country code, variable is years, and value is the CO2 emission. With those information in mind, we will now begin tiding the data.

In [380]:
# Keep Country code and year column, melt all other columns into Kt.
co2 = pd.melt(co2, id_vars=['Country Code'], var_name="Year", value_name='Kt') # Tidy CO2 DF.

First, we will need to left-join CO2 and population based on Country Code and Year.

Handle with Missing Data¶

At this point, we want to check the number of instance of nan in each column. And handle the missing data appropriately.

In [388]:
co2.isnull().sum()
Out[388]:

Year               0
Kt              2299

Region          2585
IncomeGroup     2585
dtype: int64

After mannually reviewing country's metadata, we can positively confirm alll instances where region and incomegroup where missing are not countries. They are the aggregate of multiple countires based on regions or other indicators such as income. Therefore, we can remove all of rows where Region and IncomeGroup are empty.

In [389]:
# Remove the row if region and incomegroup are nan.
co2 = co2.dropna(subset=['Region','IncomeGroup'])
co2.isnull().sum()
Out[389]:
Country_Code       0
Year               0
Kt              2079
Population       104
Region             0
IncomeGroup        0
dtype: int64

Now, the number of null in region and incomeGroup columns is 0 as expected. However, the null instances of population and Kt didn't drop a lot. Now, we need to fill the missing data. One of the best ways is to fill the missing data is based on regession.

The regression formula to used to fill the missing co2 data will be Kt = Year * Country_Code.

In [390]:
co2_regression = smf.ols(formula='Kt ~ Year * Country_Code ', data=co2).fit()

print(co2_regression.summary())

# Func to fill missing co2
def find_missing_co2(row):
    if not math.isnan(row['Kt']):
        return row['Kt'] # return the data if is not nan
    else:
        # Predict co2 in Kt.
        temp = co2_regression.predict(pd.DataFrame({'Country_Code':[row['Country_Code']],'Year': row['Year']}))
        if (float(temp) >= 0):
            return float(temp) # CO2 amount needs to be >=0, otherwise it will distorte the distort.
        else:
            return 0 # cannot return less than zero.
        
        

# Apply the calc_residual to the new column named residual in data PD.
co2['new_Kt'] = co2.apply(find_missing_co2, axis=1)
In [393]:
# Func to fill missing population
def find_missing_pop(row):
    if not math.isnan(row['Population']):
        return row['Population'] # return the data if is not nan
    else:
        temp = float(co2_regression.predict(pd.DataFrame({'Country_Code':[row['Country_Code']],'Year': row['Year']})))
        # Population need to be bigger than 1; otherwise the co2_ppl will not work (CO2/0)
        if temp >=1:
            temp
        else:
            return 1
        

# Apply the calc_residual to the new column named residual in data PD.
co2['new_pop'] = co2.apply(find_missing_pop, axis=1)

Visualizing Year, Population, and CO2 in 3D Plot.¶

Creating a 3D plot will help us to visualize the relationship between year, population, and CO2 in a better way. With 2D line plot, we can only visualize the relationship between at most two types. In the 3D plot, the X axis will be Year, Y axis is Population, and CO2 on Z axis. Plot.ly provides a convenient way to do this. Details can be found at: https://plot.ly/python/3d-scatter-plots/ .

In [401]:

There are some interesting facts one can observe from the 3D plot above. As expected, different countries have different rates of CO2 emission growth. Some countries growth at a near exp rate while some other stays almost identical. Additionally, the rise in population does not always correspond to rise in CO2 emission. Some countries have dropped in CO2 emission while has population growth.

Global CO2 Per Person Over Time¶

This creates an interesting question. Based on the two 2D line graphs shown before, one can easily understand that the rise in population is accompanied by the rise in population. But how about CO2 per person (based on CO2/Population)? It is not very obvious in those plots. Therefore, we would like to perform a calculation to retrieve the information.

We did calculate the CO2 per person previously for each country in each year. However, the data cannot be directly used for aggregated CO2 per person around the world. The reason being that if country A has population 1000 with 1000 Kt CO2 emission in that year, CO2 per ppl in that country is 1. Country B has population 10 with 100 Kt CO2 emission, CO2 per ppl is 10 in this case. Simplely (1+10)/2 = 5.5 is different from the aggregates which is (1000+100)/(1000+10)=1.089.

In [402]:
# SUM of CO2 around the world / SUM of Pop around the world
co2_ppl = np.divide(co2_by_year.values, pop_by_year.values) *1000 # Result in Metric Ton where 1 Kt = 100 T

# Trace the data into scatter plot
trace = go.Scatter(
    x = co2_by_year.index.values,
    y = co2_ppl
)

# Title, axis info.
layout = go.Layout(
    title='Global CO2 Per Person Over Time',
    xaxis=dict(
        title='Year'
    ),
    yaxis=dict(
        title='CO2 Emission (Tons)'
    )
)

data = [trace]

fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)

iplot(fig)

The CO2 Per Person overtime graph is very interesting. It was rising very quickly in the late 1960s, stable in 1970s. Then, it was dropped in the early 1980s. It did not start rising again after 2000. Then, the line raised dramatically.

Machine Learning¶

In this section, we would like to use machine learning to predict the future growth the CO2 emission around the world. There are two ways to find CO2 emission in the global scale. One is directly predict the CO2 emission using historical CO2 emission data. Another one is based on CO per person.

ML using CO2 Data¶

In [406]:
# Group the CO2 data by year to find the sum of co2 emission by year
co2_by_year = co2.groupby('Year')['Kt'].sum()

trace = []

# Sepearate the x, y into own np.array.
x = co2_by_year.index.values
y = co2_by_year.values


# check for polyfit from degree 1 to 5
for i in range(1, 6):
    z = np.polyfit(x, y, i) # np.polyfit with ith degree
    poly = np.poly1d(z)
    yfit = np.polyval(z,pop_x) # Y-fit

    residual = np.sum((co2_per_ppl-yfit)**2) # calc residual
    print("Residual for " + str(i) + ': ' +str(residual)) # print out residual.

    temp_x = []
    temp_y = []
    
    # For each year betwen 1960 to 2050, predict the data.
    for t in range(1960, 2051):
        temp_x = np.append(temp_x,[t])
        temp_y = np.append(temp_y,[poly(t)])
    
    trace.append(go.Scatter(
        x = temp_x,
        y = temp_y,
        name = "Polyfit: " + str(i)
    ))
    
# Create a trace
trace.append(go.Scatter(
    x = x,
    y = y,
    name = "Real"
))

Insight & Policy Decision¶

Throughout the tutorial, we discovered some key insights from the CO2 data, graphs, and machine learning results. To sum up some of them, here is a list of insights:

  • Global CO2 emissions is currently more than 32M Kt per year in 2014, almost three times the amount in 1960s.
  • Upper middle income group over take high income group total CO2 emission in late 2000s and become the NO.1 emitter.
  • China is currently the largest CO2 emitter, almost as twice as much as U.S.A.
  • East Asia and pacific is the No.1 emitter region in the world, around 14M Kt in 2014.
  • Without CO2 policy control, global CO2 emission could reach 45M kt per year and more than 8 Tons per person per year in 2050.

CO2 emission and global warming are very serious topics. It is nice to see the world could come together in the Paris climate agreement to flight to reduce the temperature rising. While it is disappointing that current U.S. administration leaves the agreement, each individual could fight for the climate in their own ways. It is our reponsibility as a human being to protect our home, the earth.
